1:---
2:title: "Some Random Observations"
3:author: ["E.T. Jaynes"]
4:year: 1985
5:---
6:## Introduction {#introduction .unnumbered}
7:When told of the plan to devote an issue of Synthese to the principle of
8:maximum entropy (PME), my first reaction was puzzlement as to why
9:philosophers should be so interested in it. Then a plausible reason
10:appeared to be that PME has been perceived (correctly, in my view) as a
11:small but nonnegligible part of a fundamental revolution in thought now
12:taking place.
13:
14:We have the analysis of Kuhn describing how new foundation concepts make
15:their way into science; but today in order to study this one does not
16:need to go back to the history books to read of epicycles and ellipses.
17:We can observe in our midst the phenomenon of one paradigm in the
18:process of being replaced by another.
